<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Lilley applauds pensions boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pensioners are now receiving far greater sums from private sources of income
than they did when the Conservatives first came to power in 1979, social
security ministers told MPs yesterday.
In a series of answers to Commons questions, Mr Peter Lilley, social
security secretary, said pensioners were considerably better off as a result
of private-pension schemes and other forms of income.
Mr Lilley said the average pensioner's income from savings and occupational
pensions had risen some 125 per cent in real terms between 1979 and 1991 to
Pounds 63.20.
Mr William Hague, a junior minister at the department, said facilities owned
by pensioners had improved sharply in recent years.
Mr Hague claimed that 90 per cent of pensioners had a television set, that
the number of pensioners with cars had doubled since 1979 and that the
percentage with the lowest 10 per cent of incomes had dropped from 31 per
cent to 11 per cent since 1979.
Both ministers were marshalling the argument about improved living standards
for pensioners ahead of an opposition-led debate on the pensions industry
later this week. Labour MPs will argue that many pensioners' incomes have
been blighted because they have been sold private pension schemes unsuitable
for them.
</TEXT>
