<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Injuries scheme attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday rejected calls for changes to the criminal injuries
compensation scheme, in spite of Labour's warnings that thousands of victims
would be worse off because of it.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said about a quarter of victims would
'lose substantially', and those who were losing out would often be the worst
injured.
During the report stage debate of the criminal justice and public order
bill, Mr Blair said: 'There is nothing that (more) completely exposes the
hollowness of government claims on law and order than the scrapping of the
existing system of criminal injuries compensation.'
The government is refusing to rethink the proposed changes, which would
replace individual assessments with a fixed tariff.
The reforms have been criticised in the Lords, where peers said they could
be unconstitutional and open to judicial review.
However, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, is understood to have taken
legal advice which supports the government view that the changes can be
implemented.
Mr Blair said the present scheme would be replaced by one 'based on a crude
tariff, which will ignore the individual circumstances of the victim'.
The existing system, introduced in 1964, compensated victims of violence on
roughly the same basis as civil law and took into account future loss of
earnings.
Mr Blair urged withdrawal of the new system until the government established
a better scheme, 'properly consulted upon, properly worked out, that
protects the interests of the victim in the way the British public wishes to
see'.
Mr Robert Maclennan, for the Liberal Democrats, accused Mr Howard of acting
'high-handedly and possibly illegally'.
</TEXT>
