<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Israelis shoot dead six Fatah activists: Deaths cast shadow
on Hebron security talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON and DAVID HOROWITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
In the bloodiest single incident since last month's Hebron mosque massacre,
Israeli undercover troops shot dead six Palestinians and seriously injured a
seventh in Gaza's Jebalya refugee camp yesterday.
The dead men were identified by local residents as members of Mr Yassir
Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction of the PLO, and their deaths cast a shadow
over today's scheduled resumption of talks in Cairo between Israeli and PLO
delegations trying to agree on protective measures for the Palestinians of
Hebron. Last week, the Israeli army's killing of four Hamas Islamic
militants in Hebron almost forced a suspension of the talks, and it seems
likely that Mr Arafat would be more sensitive to the deaths of his own
loyalists.
Yesterday's incident occurred shortly after PLO supporters had held a
memorial ceremony in Gaza's Sheikh Radwan neighbourhood for a Fatah activist
killed a month ago by the Israeli army. Two carloads of Fatah supporters
were returning to Jebalya when, according to Israeli military sources, they
were spotted by undercover troops and ordered to halt. The army claimed the
Fatah men ignored the order and fired on the soldiers, who shot back.
Three Palestinian youths standing near the cars were also slightly hurt. The
army claimed the dead men were found to have been armed, but witnesses
denied this and said they were simply handing out leaflets to passers-by
through the car windows. State television said last night that the army had
closed off the immediate area, and was considering placing much of Gaza
under curfew.
Israeli and Palestinian officials could seal agreement by today on security
measures to protect Palestinians in Hebron, they said yesterday. This should
lead to the immediate resumption of suspended talks on Israeli withdrawal
from Gaza and Jericho.
Mr Nabill Shaath, chief PLO negotiator, said the two sides had 'gone a long
and important way' in the talks and only 'some points' remained at issue.
PLO officials in Tunis said the differences were over the precise number of
international observers and Palestinian police to be deployed in Hebron, and
some details of their jurisdiction and rules of deployment.
The Israelis want to limit the observer force to 60 officers, to be supplied
by Norway, and the Palestinian force to a few dozen. The PLO is seeking 150
observers and 400 police. Mr Shaath said the PLO was awaiting responses to
its demands from Israel. 'We are not going to discuss anything else until we
finish this agreement,' he added.
Both sides appear eager to return to full peace talks as soon as possible.
However, while PLO officials in Tunis said they still hoped Israeli
withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho could begin as scheduled on April 13,
Israeli officials have suggested the talks might need 'a few weeks' to
conclude agreement.
</TEXT>
