<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / California defiant in unitary tax case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
California has a perfect constitutional right to reimpose unitary taxation
tomorrow, the state's lawyers told the US Supreme Court yesterday as they
defended their use of the controversial tax assessment method against
Barclays Bank of the UK.
'Politically, would that happen? Probably not, but what we are dealing with
is a political question,' said Mr Timothy Laddish, California's assistant
attorney general.
Under pressure from the Clinton administration, California's legislature
last year stopped imposing its unitary tax system, which calculated tax on a
proportion of a group's worldwide income, rather than just on income earned
in the state.
The case revolves around a contested tax assessment of Dollars 154,000, but
interest and associated cases have raised the stakes for California to a
total of Dollars 800m.
In the Supreme Court yesterday, Mr Drew Days, the Clinton administration's
solicitor general, argued unitary taxation might have become
unconstitutional after 1985, because it conflicted with administration
policy and thus prevented the federal government from speaking with one
voice. But Mr Days said that in 1977, the year at issue in the case brought
by Barclays against California, the government had expressed 'a preference,
and not a policy'.
Although Mr Days's arguments were meant to support California, Mr Laddish
said that he was wrong: the unitary method was not only a 'user-friendly
system of reasonable apportionment', it remained constitutional, because
Congress had quite clearly refused to outlaw it.
Judging by their questions yesterday - an uncertain indication of voting
intentions - two of the nine Supreme Court justices appeared to incline
towards Barclays, while four seemed to favour California.
</TEXT>
<XX>
