<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Olivetti bid wins Italian telecoms licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN SIMKINS and ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN, ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Italian government last night awarded the hotly contested licence for
its new Europe-wide GSM standard mobile telecommunications network to a
consortium led by the Olivetti computer group.
The contract was awarded to the Omnitel-Pronto Italia consortium on the eve
of the country's general election results. The losing consortium was Unitel,
a joint venture led by Fiat and including Fininvest, the holding company of
media magnate Silvio Berlusconi, Vodafone and BellSouth.
The decision had been pending for several days but the timing of the Ciampi
government's decision appeared linked to the likelihood of Mr Berlusconi's
Forza Italia movement being on the winning side in the elections.
Omnitel-Pronto Italia won on technical grounds and by virtue of the higher
fee that will be paid to the government - L750bn (Pounds 304m).
The licence to run Italy's second mobile phones network, in competition with
the Sip state telephone utility, which until now has held the monopoly, has
been estimated as worth up to L4,300bn (Pounds 1.7bn) although the heavy
investment required means profits are unlikely in the first few years of
operation.
Olivetti, which will provide 35 per cent of the investment by the winning
consortium (grouping Bell Atlantic, Pactel and Mannesmann) needs to provide
L200bn over eight years. Although Olivetti's board will ask shareholders for
authorisation, if necessary, for a rights issue up to L1 trillion, Mr Carlo
De Benedetti, chairman, has ruled out a capital increase this year.
Olivetti plans to use the licence as a key part of a new high-tech network
to serve mobile phone and computer users. The company, which had net losses
of L460bn in 1993, has sought increasingly to shift from unprofitable
hardware into services.
The contest was narrowed to two consortiums after two mergers between the
original four applicants.
The decision injects further pace into the restructuring of Italy's
telecommunications industry following agreement to merge five network
operators under the state-controlled Stet telecoms utility - itself due to
be privatised this year.
The cellular phones market is being opened up in Italy after pressure from
the European Commission and rapid growth is expected. The total sales of Sip
increased by 8.6 per cent last year to L23.4bn.
</TEXT>
