<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / S African leaders call emergency summit after 18 die in gun
battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN and PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
South Africa's political leaders last night called an emergency summit after
gun battles in the heart of Johannesburg's business district left at least
18 people dead and provoked calls for a state of emergency to control
violence ahead of next month's elections.
Thousands of Inkatha Freedom party supporters, staging an anti-election
march in South Africa's commercial capital, attempted to storm the
headquarters of the African National Congress. ANC security guards shot at
them, killing at least eight.
Witnesses said the marchers were also shot at outside the city library,
where several were killed by snipers firing from nearby buildings. Police
said at least 50 people were injured, but independent sources, who put the
death toll at 31, indicated that the casualty figure could be higher.
In response to the mayhem, South Africa's four most important political
leaders - President FW de Klerk, ANC leader Mr Nelson Mandela, Inkatha
leader Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi and Zulu King Goodwill Zwelethini - are to
meet together for the first time at a two-day summit beginning tomorrow.
They will discuss ANC demands that troops be sent to Natal province, where
at least 55 people were killed last weekend.
The Johannesburg killings aroused the country's worst fears of growing
violence forcing the delay or abandonment of next month's first all-race
elections unless brought under control.
Mr Thabo Mbeki, ANC chairman, said a state of emergency would have to be
considered to ensure the poll could take place from April 26 to 28.
President de Klerk said the time had come for 'urgent consideration . . . of
additional measures or steps which can prevent a repetition of what has
happened today'.
Tension had been building for several days, with Inkatha supporters angered
by ANC threats to depose Chief Buthelezi and his KwaZulu administration.
For the first time in a decade of violence in and around Johannesburg,
large-scale unrest broke out in the city centre itself, within earshot of
the Johannesburg Stock Exchange where share prices fell sharply. The city
was last night declared an 'unrest area' by Mr Hernus Kriel, minister of law
and order, giving police special powers.
In past outbreaks of political violence, South African leaders have rapidly
stabilised the position. But as the election draws closer, defusing crises
has become more difficult.
Fiscal discipline, Page 6
</TEXT>
