<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Cabinet poised to accept deal over EU voting rights: Tory
backbenchers angry over 'climbdown'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The government was last night preparing to accept the proposed compromise
with its European partners over voting rights. The move should pave the way
for four new members to enter the Union next January.
But as Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, awaited cabinet endorsement
of the arrangement this morning, Mr Major, the prime minister, was accused
on the Conservative backbenches of reneging on pledges to strike a harder
bargain.
To limit the potential backlash among Tory MPs, Mr Hurd was awaiting urgent
assurances from the European Commission that in future it will not seek to
circumvent Britain's opt-out from the social provisions of the Maastricht
treaty.
The foreign secretary expects to receive this morning a written commitment
from Mr Jacques Delors, the Commission president, that in future Brussels
will not use health and safety legislation to frustrate the opt-out.
The compromise - tabled at a weekend meeting of EU foreign ministers in
Greece - raises to 27 from the present 23 the number of votes required to
block decisions in the Council of Ministers once the Union is enlarged.
But it allows for a legally enforceable pause in decision-making when
countries muster between 23 and 27 votes. It also stresses that the new
arrangement is an interim one, with the whole question of the relative
voting strengths of small and large EU countries to be reopened in 1996.
With the other 11 EU governments expected to endorse it, senior Brussels
diplomats said the UK had little choice but to do likewise or risk
triggering a crisis with its other EU partners over enlargement. Sir Leon
Brittan, the senior British commissioner in Brussels, also urged acceptance.
But the consensus at Westminster was that by encouraging his supporters to
believe he would take a more determined stance, Mr Major had again damaged
his political authority.
Anticipating the anger also of rightwing ministers about an arrangement
which falls short of Britain's original demands, Mr Hurd refused publicly to
anticipate the cabinet's decision.
But, speaking in the House of Commons, he made it clear that his own
political authority rested on an accord which he insisted had safeguarded
Britain's interests without delaying the entry into the EU of Finland,
Sweden, Norway and Austria.
Other pivotal figures in the cabinet, including Mr Kenneth Clarke, Mr
Michael Heseltine and Mr David Hunt, offered Mr Hurd their full backing.
That left cabinet Eurosceptics such as Mr Peter Lilley, Mr Michael Portillo
and Mr John Redwood the stark options of backing the compromise or
resigning. Despite some speculation that Mr Lilley might consider such a
course, the judgment of most ministers was that it was not an issue on which
the cabinet's sceptics would make a public stand.
Close friends of Mr Hurd also dismissed suggestions that the latest row has
persuaded him to stand down as foreign secretary when Mr Major reshuffles
the cabinet in the summer. The friends insisted that Mr Hurd wants to stay
at the Foreign Office at least until mid-1995.
The foreign secretary stressed repeatedly his view that the proposed accord
had gone as far as he thought possible. Stressing the legal status of the
proposed pause and its interim nature, Mr Hurd gave the impression that in
practical terms the blocking minority would stay at 23 votes. But he
admitted that once efforts to secure an agreement on that basis had been
exhausted, the new position meant decisions could in fact be pushed through
on the basis of a minority of 27.
In Brussels, officials said the compromise expressly excluded an open-ended
discussion on decisions which were opposed by countries mustering between 23
and 26 votes in the council.
The draft text says: 'The council will do all in its power to reach, within
a reasonable time and without prejudicing obligatory time limits laid down
by the treaties and by secondary law . . . a satisfactory solution.'
Braced for a deal, Page 12
Joe Rogaly, Page 20
A Europe that deserves support, Page 21
Editorial Comment and Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
