<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Berlusconi alliance heads for clear win in Italian poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Media magnate Mr Silvio Berlusconi last night staked his claim to head
Italy's next government, after initial projections gave his three-party
rightwing Freedom Alliance a clear lead over his rivals in elections for
parliament.
Mr Berlusconi, who turned to politics less than four months ago after
scandals demolished many veteran politicians, pledged to relaunch the
economy with a free-market programme. But he acknowledged he would have
difficulty in putting together a government with his allies in the Freedom
Alliance - the populist Northern League of Mr Umberto Bossi and Mr
Gianfranco Fini of the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance. 'We must be united
in victory,' he declared.
Computer projections based on partial counting of votes indicated that the
Freedom Alliance would be the largest bloc and was likely to win an absolute
majority in the lower house, the Chamber of Deputies. One projection early
today suggested it could get as many as 375 seats in the 630-member chamber.
The Freedom Alliance appeared less likely to gain a working majority in the
upper house, the Senate, which has power to block legislation. But one
projection gave it 150-160 seats in the 315-member Senate. Final results are
not expected to be known until tonight after two days of voting under an
experimental system mixing first-past-the-post and proportional
representation.
A dejected Mr Achille Occhetto, leader of the Party of the Democratic Left
(PDS) - which co-ordinated the leftwing Progressive Alliance - conceded his
seven-party grouping had failed to win enough support to determine the next
government.
The centre alliance, composed of former Christian Democrats in the Popular
Party (PPI) and the centrist pact of Mr Mario Segni, was squeezed. Early
projections gave the Italian Pact 45-65 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
The result is an extraordinary personal success for Mr Berlusconi, whose
Forza Italia movement appeared to have won about 25 per cent of the vote
nationwide. The Milan-born Mr Berlusconi looked set to win his own
first-past-the-post contest in Rome against Prof Luigi Spaventa, the budget
minister and candidate for the Progressives.
Another big success was the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, which exit
polls showed to have won 13 per cent of the vote.
Signalling tension in the Freedom Alliance, Mr Bossi said the victory was
one of a 'reactionary right' and he accused the neo-fascists of 'trying to
open up the wallets of the north' to aid the poorer south.
The Italian financial markets had surged yesterday with strong buying based
on reports that the Freedom Alliance was likely to win. The Milan stock
market's main index added 3.76 per cent.
