<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Italian markets surge on poll leaks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and JOHN SIMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME, MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's financial markets surged yesterday with strong buying based on
reports that the right-wing Freedom Alliance, headed by media magnate Mr
Silvio Berlusconi, was likely to win an overall parliamentary majority.
The Milan stock market's main index added 3.76 per cent, while the lira
strengthened against the dollar and the D-Mark on hopes of a stable
government. 'The market got stronger and stronger as rumours were spread of
a Berlusconi victory,' said Mr Alberto Rolla of securities house Milla.
Reaction in the markets was based on leaked exit polls conducted by at least
three organisations during Sunday's voting in the country's general
election. It did not take account of yesterday's second and final day of
voting when polling stations were due to close at 10 pm local time.
Electoral regulations banned the publication of exit polls until the
stations had closed, but leaks gave between 46 per cent and 51 per cent of
the vote to the Freedom Alliance, composed of Mr Berlusconi's Forza Italia
movement, the populist Northern League of Mr Umberto Bossi and the
neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance of Mr Gianfranco Fini.
On the basis of these polls, the Freedom Alliance could have as many as 340
seats in the 630-seat chamber of deputies.
In contrast, the seven-party Progressive Alliance headed by the former
communist Party of the Democratic Left would have about 240 seats. The
centre Italian Pact, headed by Mr Mario Segni, would have a maximum of 60
seats.
Throughout the day political analysts continued to voice caution about
predicting the outcome. They pointed out that exit polls might be unable to
measure accurately the returns from Italy's experiment with two different
election systems - a first-past-the-post method covering 75 per cent of the
seats and proportional representation for the remainder.
It was also far from clear yesterday whether Forza Italia's northern
electoral ally, the Northern League, would be part of a government coalition
formed by the Freedom Alliance.
Speaking before the count yesterday, Mr Marco Formentini, the Northern
League mayor of Milan, stressed that his federalist party would not join the
National Alliance in government.
He said that for this reason it was important for the Northern League and
Forza Italia to stay together and that it might be possible to find other
allies with which to form a government.
Government bonds, Page 32 Currencies, Page 37 World stocks, Page 43
