<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Ministers to back bill on leases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is set to back a Conservative MP's bill to change the law of
privity of contract in England and Wales in a move which could mean that
reforms to commercial leases are enacted as early as this summer.
The bill - being prepared by Mr Peter Thurnham, Tory MP for Bolton North
East - would abolish the convention, peculiar to England and Wales, by which
an original tenant in a commercial property lease is liable to pay the rent
if a subsequent tenant defaults.
The Lord Chancellor's Department said yesterday that the government would
support any private member's bill that was close to its own proposals.
Mr Thurnham said he was confident that his bill - which would be drafted
'very shortly' - would receive 'very strong backing from all sides of the
House of Commons'.
It has long been the government's intention to reform this aspect of the law
but ministers have been unable to find the parliamentary time needed for a
bill to be enacted.
Business leaders have been prominent among those calling for change. Earlier
this month Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of
British Industry, cited a bill reforming privity of contract as an example
of the type of legislation - helpful to the business community - that he
would like to see ministers accommodate in the parliamentary timetable.
Parliamentary procedures make it far from certain that Mr Thurnham's bill
will reach the statute book even if it is backed by ministers. Private
member's bills can be blocked by the opposition of one MP.
Opposition is expected to the change on the grounds that limiting a tenant's
responsibility for paying rent throughout a lease is likely to reduce the
security of a building's income and so the value of a landlord's investment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
