<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Courtaulds plans Pounds 80m plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Financial Times Reporter
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The board of Courtaulds, the chemicals and textiles group, is expected to
approve in the next few days the spending of about Pounds 80m on a European
plant to produce Tencel, its new synthetic fabric.
The plant is to be sited either at Grimsby on Humberside or near Munich in
Germany.
The approval is expected almost to coincide with a long-delayed agreement by
Courtaulds and Hoechst, the German chemicals company, to merge their
European viscose and acrylic fibres operations under Courtaulds' control.
Courtaulds said yesterday it hoped that the merger, first announced in May
last year but delayed by competition-authority scrutiny, would be signed
before the end of this week. A decision on where to locate the Tencel plant
will follow soon.
Courtaulds wants the plant running in 1996 to cater for what it says will be
surging world demand for the material, which is made from wood pulp and said
to combine the toughness of denim with the feel of silk.
Courtaulds is supplying Tencel to all main markets, including Europe, from
an 18,000 tonnes-a-year facility in Alabama, where a second plant to
increase capacity to more than 40,000 tonnes a year is due to be operating
soon.
The European plant will increase capacity to well over 50,000 tonnes a year
and supply some Far East markets as well as those in Europe.
Because the production processes for Tencel are highly automated, employment
at such a facility is likely to be measured in dozens rather than hundreds.
The company said yesterday that the rival advantages of Grimsby and Munich
had still to be fully weighed.
</TEXT>
