<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Marshall acquires Bedford marque from GM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Marshall, the Cambridgeshire-based vehicle and aerospace group, has struck a
deal with General Motors under which it has acquired world marketing rights
to the Bedford commercial vehicle name and bought the entire Bedford truck
and bus parts business.
The deal is expected to lead to a substantial increase in Marshall's truck
production this year, from 400 to about 600.
Executives of Marshall SPV, the umbrella company for Marshall's vehicle
operations, regard the acquisition of the parts business as at least as
important because of the large number of Bedford vehicles on the world's
roads.
Mr Dick Revell, Marshall SPV's parts director, said at the weekend: 'On a
conservative estimate there are at least 500,000 out there.' Bedford, which
has a 60-year history, was once the world's largest truckmaker. GM sold the
Bedford truckmaking business for Pounds 22m in 1987, when it was losing
Pounds 500,000 a week, to the entrepreneur Mr David Brown, who renamed it
AWD. At one time under Mr Brown's ownership AWD was employing more than
1,300 people and making more than 5,000 trucks a year.
After the business went into receivership in June 1992 Marshall bought from
the receivers AWD's product designs, order book, rights to the AWD name and
limited rights to the Bedford name.
Marshall executives believe that a significant reason for AWD's failure was
that its own deal with GM did not include the consistently profitable parts
business. Most truckmakers earn most of their revenue from replacement parts
rather than new vehicle sales.
Neither Vauxhall Motors, GM's UK subsidiary which is the formal signatory to
the deal, nor Marshall - a reticent company which prefers to conduct its
affairs out of the public spotlight - would give any financial details of
the agreement.
One measure of the size of the parts business, however, is that Marshall has
already shipped 170 articulated truckloads of parts to warehouses and
distribution sites in Kent from the former Bedford factory at Dunstable,
Bedfordshire.
Marshall SPV was originally set up as Marshall of Cambridge (Engineering) to
make vehicle bodies and exploit the international market for specialist
military vehicles such as field ambulances. It changed its name two years
ago and has extended its activities in the civilian vehicles field. Its
range includes refuse disposal vehicles, single-decker buses and car
transporters and trailers. It also owns Carlisle, the Birmingham-based
busmaker. Mr Bob Crosby, the UK sales manager, said the company had no
intention of re-entering the mainstream commercial market for trucks.
Marshall has been awarded exclusive rights to the Bedford name and trademark
throughout Europe. Its rights outside Europe are non-exclusive, although
GM's own use of the Bedford name - confined to a few developing world
markets - relates only to light vehicles such as Isuzu-built pick-ups.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
