<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / US group to open car parts factory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRW, the US motor, space and defence multinational, is to set up its fourth
motor components plant near Nissan's Sunderland car factory, creating 160
jobs.
TRW is investing Pounds 8m in the plant at Houghton-le-Spring, Wearside. It
will produce electronic trigger mechanisms for safety air bags, one of the
fastest-growing sectors of the motor components industry.
TRW's three existing plants in the area make switches, engine valves and
seat-belt systems - not exclusively for Nissan.
The air-bag mechanism will be exported throughout Europe. Recruitment is to
start early in the summer, with the plant expected on stream by the end of
the year.
The new facility is the latest in a series of motor component manufacturing
investments in the north, and lifts to about 30 the number of such companies
located close to the Nissan plant. When Nissan started production in 1986
only three suppliers were located in the north-east.
Nissan, which employs about 5,000 people at the Sunderland site, says it has
generated about 3,000 jobs at component suppliers based either on its car
factory site or in the north-east.
