<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Redwood to hit at 'unnecessary' green regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A rightwing cabinet minister will today launch an assault on unnecessary
environmental regulations.
In a fresh indication of how economic hardship has pushed 'green' issues
down the political agenda, Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary, will
announce a review to assess whether all protected areas in the principality
need to be so protected.
In his address to Tory activists in Port Talbot, West Glamorgan, Mr Redwood
will also touch on subsidiarity by arguing that planning decisions should be
left wherever possible to local councillors.
It should be up to councillors to decide whether to give priority to jobs or
wildlife, he will say. 'We are not in the business of frustrating people who
want new jobs and new homes.'
In remarks which will do little to further the efforts of Mr John Gummer,
environment secretary, to build a 'green' image for the government, Mr
Redwood will argue that environmentalism in Wales has tended to develop in a
'random' way. He will say the Welsh Office's efforts to encourage prosperity
are often blocked by environmental regulations from London or Brussels.
In his efforts to restore a higher-profile government approach to
environmental issues, Mr Gummer recently attacked the encroachment of 'urban
sprawl' on the countryside and the construction of shopping malls outside
towns.
Last month he called for tighter protection for green belts - areas where
development is curbed in order to prevent growing towns from joining
together.
Last November a report from the Government Statistical Service cast doubt on
the success of the government initiative to regenerate the south Wales
valleys, saying manufacturing jobs created had been more than offset by job
losses.
This prompted Mr Redwood to make a strong defence of the initiative, saying
it was important to persuade new investors that 'this was a beautiful part
of Wales with a future, and not just a scarred piece of Wales with a past
that had gone wrong'.
