<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Roadbuilding programme set for small cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The outcome of the long-awaited review of Britain's Pounds 23bn roads
programme, due to be announced on Wednesday, is expected to show a trimming
of roadbuilding schemes rather than deep cuts.
Most motorway-widening schemes are set to stay largely intact in spite of
fierce protests from lobbyists and backbench Tory MPs.
The overall reduction in planned roadbuilding activity may be no more than
10 per cent or 15 per cent. This is unlikely to ease pressure on the
department from MPs of all parties and from other government departments.
Transport 2000, a pressure group, said: 'It is likely to intensify rather
than quell concerns about the roads programme.'
Road priorities have been under review since last August, when it became
clear that the 10-year Roads for Prosperity programme, launched in 1989, was
falling well behind schedule. The aim is to reduce planning blight - the
adverse impact on property prices from roadbuilding announcements - and to
allow the department to speed up work on the most realistic schemes.
The present programme involves nearly 500 projects, including the widening
of 600 miles of motorway, expanding single-carriageway trunk roads to dual
carriageway and building more than 150 bypasses. It also includes upgrades
of the A1 and A74 to motorway standard.
The review has taken traffic forecasts into account. It is expected to
confirm existing government policy to improve existing roads rather than to
build new ones and to avoidupgrading radial routes in large cities.
There is not expected to be any radical change in the environmental criteria
applied to road schemes.
The British Roads Federation said it expected the government to go ahead
with motorway widening plans because of their economic importance. It said:
'We don't expect the motorway network to grow much over the next 100 years
so the roads we have must have a high capacity.'
The RAC said it did not expect large cuts in the roads programme but it was
concerned that some bypass schemes might be dropped.
Publication of the roads review is expected to coincide with the launch of
the government's Highways Agency. This will take over responsibility for the
road building and maintenance programme to speed up schemes and reduce
costs.
</TEXT>
