<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / IoD slams CBI on works councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Institute of Directors has criticised its rival employers' body, the
Confederation of British Industry, for accepting the principle of a
trans-national European works council for talks with employees.
The issue of works councils, which has been a subject of intense debate for
20 years, comes to a head tomorrow when negotiations on the subject between
Unice, the European employers' body, and the European Trades Union Congress
are set to break down.
A breakdown will make it almost certain that the European Commission will
pass a directive on the issue early next year.
Although Britain's Maastricht treaty social 'opt-out' means UK companies
will not be hit in the UK, 70 or 80 British multinationals will be effected
in continental Europe and are unlikely to exclude their UK employees.
The IoD is still, however, furious with the CBI, the largest single member
of Unice, for conceding in negotiations that 'minimum requirements' can be
enforced in the event of companies and employees failing to reach agreement.
European employers have accepted the goal of consultation but insisted that
there should be flexibility about how it is delivered. Mr Peter Morgan,
director-general of the IoD, believes, however, that the wording of the
latest Unice-ETUC agreement amounts to an 'own goal' in accepting a works
council-type forum.
Mr Morgan said: 'We urge the CBI and other national employer organisations
in the member states of the EU to rethink their position on Unice's
negotiations with the ETUC and to oppose proposals which would require
companies to set up union-dominated works councils.'
The IoD believes that even if the ETUC rejects the Unice position next week
 -because of disagreements about the level in the company at which the works
council should operate - European companies will find it more difficult to
argue against the idea.
</TEXT>
