<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Fears mount over laws on late payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Small-business lobby groups pressing for companies to have a statutory right
to interest on commercial debts that are paid late said yesterday that they
believed the government would not back legislation.
They suspect that Lord Strathclyde, the small business minister, favours
non-statutory methods to persuade companies to publicise their payment
record in order to 'shame' the late payers into improving their payment
records.
The views of the lobby groups emerged amid confusion about the government's
intentions, during a consultation period which is due to end this week.
Newspaper reports suggested that tough laws could be on the way but both the
Treasury and the Department of Trade and Industry were adamant yesterday
that such speculation was premature and no decisions had been taken.
According to Lord Strathclyde the government was taking the idea of
legislating on late payment 'fairly seriously' while recognising that there
was 'no point in doing it unless it will make a difference'.
He said the Federation of Small Businesses had told him it did not regard
legislation as the top priority.
Lord Strathclyde rejected the notion of imposing a standard period for
payment of debt. He said: 'People should be free to decide what the terms of
credit should be.' But he said ministers would decide on whether to
legislate on making people comply with contracts.
Companies and business groups have until Thursday to make submissions on the
government's consultative document, which was issued after Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, put the issue on the agenda in his November Budget.
The Department of Trade and Industry is expected to take a couple of months
to digest more than 200 submissions before deciding what, if anything, it
will do to address a problem that many companies say is increasingly
serious.
Some small-business lobby groups said the government showed no sign of
shedding a conviction that legislation was not the way to alleviate the
problem.
The issue has split the small-business community along some unexpected
lines. Ranked against the legislation is the Confederation of British
Industry, which says its small business members have recently become more
opposed to the legislation as it might do more harm than good.
The 58,000-strong Federation of Small Businesses - formerly the National
Federation of Self-Employed - is a cautious supporter of legislation, but
only if the government first takes other steps.
Such measures would include forcing the top 10,000 companies in the UK to
publish their payment records in their annual reports and moves to ensure
that any future legal judgments against late payers would be directly
enforceable by the courts.
Leading the campaign in favour of legislation is the 21,000-strong Forum of
Private Business, which has been joined by most of the high street banks and
the Institute of Directors.
Labour and the Liberal Democrats support legislation. Last week more than
200 MPs, including 80 Conservative backbenchers, signed an early day motion
calling for a statutory right to interest on overdue debts.
Editorial comment, Page 13
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
