<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Churchgoer wins tribunal backing on Sunday working
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A systems engineer who refused to work on a Sunday because it prevented him
from going to church has won his case for unfair dismissal from an
industrial tribunal.
This is the first time an industrial tribunal has ruled in an unfair
dismissal case based on the grounds of the applicant's religious beliefs.
Mr Andrew Dutton, who worked for Hughes Rediffusion Simulation at Crawley,
West Sussex, for five years, said: 'I am just an ordinary guy who did not
want to be forced to work Sundays. I tried hard to reach a compromise with
the company and failed.'
The company, a subsidiary of General Motors, wanted Mr Dutton to work up to
26 Sundays a year - which could have resulted in Sunday working for a
continuous 12 months - but he said that as a practising Christian he could
not.
A further hearing will set damages for Mr Dutton, but he is now without a
job.
Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary, welcomed the tribunal's
ruling.
He said: 'The government has fostered a climate in which employers disregard
the fundamental rights of their employees in the pursuit of profit at the
expense of dignity.'
The Keep Sunday Special Campaign, which was not involved in Mr Dutton's
case, said yesterday that the affair highlighted 'the importance of securing
adequate employment protection for employees to ensure their right to
express their religious beliefs of whatever persuasion'.
The proposed limited employee protection contained in the Sunday trading
bill going through parliament covers only those in the retail trade and not
in associated industries or other sectors. Mr Dutton won his case under the
1978 Employment Protection (Consolidation) Act.
</TEXT>
