<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Storm grows over tax increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury, yesterday
attacked Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, saying tax rises would be nearly
twice as much as he said.
The storm over the tax rises gathered momentum as Labour accused the
chancellor of pulling the wool over people's eyes about the increases. Ms
Harman said the average impact on households would be Pounds 10 a week and
not Pounds 5.75 as Mr Clarke said.
Ms Harman said: 'People will have to pay Pounds 500 more in tax from April.
They will be dismayed to see that they cannot trust the chancellor to tell
the truth about taxes.'
She said she thought the chancellor's Pounds 5.75 figure must include people
who were unemployed and not therefore paying income tax or National
Insurance.
Mr Clarke said concerns about the tax rises were 'exaggerated' and would
probably be forgotten in two months. Those frightened by reports about the
size of the increases would find they were not as bad as they expected.
Interviewed on BBC TV's On The Record, he said the average impact, taken
across all households, would be about Pounds 5.75 a week, but this figure
would vary enormously according to individual circumstances. On Saturday he
told the Conservative central council in Plymouth that this was equivalent
to 'about three or four pints of beer a week.'
Mr Clarke dismissed claims that the tax rises would stall the recovery.
Brushing aside claims that consumer confidence was faltering, the chancellor
said business confidence was much higher than a year ago and growth was
'getting stronger all the time'.
</TEXT>
