<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Clarke reforms 'heading for chaos'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reform of the tax system risked triggering 'unprecedented chaos', Mr Malcolm
Gammie, president of the Institute of Taxation, warned on Saturday.
Mr Gammie said there had been more tax legislation in his presidential year
than in any previous year since the institute was founded in 1930. He said
the latest finance bill was longer than any of its predecessors and the
volume was likely to go on rising.
He was speaking at a conference of the institute in Cambridge as it emerged
that the institute, one of the leading bodies for tax practitioners in the
country, had been granted a royal charter.
Mr Gammie called for improvements in the way tax law was drafted, reviewed
and approved by parliament in order to 'bring it into the 20th century'. He
said the length was 'beyond the grasp of those that must handle it within
the time allowed'.
He criticised suggestions that lengthy laws were required because of tax
avoidance, and said they reflected instead a policy to tax things which were
difficult to tax.
Mr Gammie said there had been little debate on whether the system was
desirable.
He called for a proper debate on tax policy and the resulting complexities
and warned that otherwise there was a risk of growing executive power
without effective scrutiny.
</TEXT>
