<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / ANC clash with Inkatha in Natal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The African National Congress said yesterday that it would escalate mass
protest action aimed at ensuring free political activity in the strife-torn
Natal province, where ANC and Inkatha Freedom party members clashed again at
the weekend over preparations for next month's all-race elections.
Government officials said Inkatha leader Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi met
President FW de Klerk for a five-hour meeting on Saturday, at which he gave
assurances that free campaigning would be allowed in the KwaZulu homeland
which he heads, and that elections could take place there despite Inkatha's
poll boycott.
However, his supporters appeared to have ignored these assurances yesterday,
when armed Zulus occupied a stadium in northern Natal where the ANC was to
have held an election rally. It was the third weekend in a row that Inkatha
had prevented an election rally in Natal.
Officials said they hoped that Chief Buthelezi's assurances to Mr de Klerk
would defuse the immediate crisis over Natal, and help persuade the ANC to
defer its demands that some of the chief's powers be suspended and a state
of emergency declared.
The ANC-dominated Transitional Executive Council, the multi-party body
overseeing government in the run-up to elections, is to meet again today to
discuss the crisis.
Chief Buthelezi said at the weekend that a troop deployment 'could be seen
as an invasion'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
