<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAR 94 / Balladur hint over youth pay: Local government elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime minister, yesterday indicated that he
may be prepared to make concessions on a controversial law which allows
young apprentices to be paid less than the minimum wage.
The law, which the government has insisted is necessary to help curb the
rise of youth unemployment, has prompted nationwide demonstrations by
hundreds of thousands of French students who demand that it be withdrawn.
Mr Balladur admitted that the law 'is regarded as displaying a lack of
attention. It is my duty as head of the government to respond to what is an
appeal from the young'.
He stopped short of offering to withdraw the law, but said he would seek to
open a dialogue with youth representatives within the next few days to
discuss possible solutions.
Mr Balladur was speaking at the end of the second and final round of
elections for regional councils, which confirmed the dominant position of
his centre-right coalition in local government, but which also brought gains
for the opposition Socialist party.
The ruling RPR-UDF coalition lost 10 seats but still took 52 per cent of the
vote, while the socialists and their allies gained seven seats with 36.6 per
cent support, according to the Interior Ministry.
The communists secured 7.7 per cent of the final vote, the extreme right
National Front 2.6 per cent and the ecologists less than 0.5 per cent.
There was a 58.7 per cent voter turnout, against 60 per cent in last week's
first round vote.
In the first round, the RPR-UDF coalition won 44.7 per cent of the vote and
the socialists 28.7 per cent.
Mr Balladur described the results as a vote of confidence in the government
and RPR-UDF coalition.
Mr Michel Rocard, the socialist leader, said the results were very
satisfying and demonstrated the recovery of the party since last year's
general election.
The local elections were the first nationwide vote since the general
election and were regarded as an important test for Mr Balladur's
government. The prime minister has seen his personal popularity decline
steadily since the beginning of the year and his approval rating now stands
at below 50 per cent.
Yesterday's elections concerned the 1,372 council seats in which there was
no outright winner in the first round of voting.
The 95 conseils generals are an important part of France's structure of
local govern-ment. Their responsibilities include the management and
development of public services, such as transport and healthcare, outside
urban areas.
</TEXT>
